item.title: Other life forms?
item.dc:creator: @LeScape_Pk LeScape Pk
item.description:
@LeScape_Pk wrote:

I believe that there is. There have been many discoveries that can hint towards this, such as the discovery of Gliese 581, it’s 20 light years from the earth, 1/3 the size of the son and 50x colder than it. It has the same atmospheric make up as earth, not to mention the stars around it that provide it with enough heat that the planet has H20. If there are things like this, there must be other life forms. Not just aliens, there are more forms of life then that, such as bacteria. With H20, comes bacteria. If Gliese 581 can have H20, then there is a 90% chance it is a place possible to be lived on. I’m sure earth was once the same way, before the big bang. The bacteria came on the water, evolution took place (evolution is not the changing over time, it’s the survival of the fittest), and civilization eventually grew. At one point or another, scientists plan to have a space elevator, and possible people living on mars. If all of this is possible, then what do you think the chances are of other life, and remember people. There are more forms of life then just aliens. Think micro-organisms.

*for those of you who don’t believe me, here is a DIRECT link to an article about Gliese 581
Gliese 581, a Duplicate Earth?
